data.content:
Your code **does not use `Thread.Abort`**, `ThreadAbortException`, or `Thread.ResetAbort`. It only uses `Thread.Start()`, `Thread.Join()`, and `Thread.Sleep()` — all of which work identically in .NET 8 with no migration needed.

**No Thread.Abort migration is required here.**

That said, for modern .NET 8, you could modernize this to use `Task`/`Parallel` for cleaner concurrency:

```csharp
public class SimpleWorker
{
    public void RunBatch(List<WorkItem> items)
    {
        Parallel.ForEach(items, item => Process(item));
    }

    private void Process(WorkItem item)
    {
        Thread.Sleep(100);
        item.Result = ComputeResult(item.Input);
    }
}
```

This gives you better thread pool utilization but is optional — your existing code will compile and run correctly on .NET 8 as-is.
